SIMPLE: jump
RECORDS: 8

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: jump
<hw>jump</hw> <pr>(j⟦ucr⟧mp)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>jupe</ets> a long petticoat, a skirt. Cf. <er>juppon</er>.]</ety>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A kind of loose jacket for men.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A bodice worn instead of stays by women in the
18th century.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>jump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: jump
<hw>jump</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>jumped</conjf> <pr>(j⟦ucr⟧mt; 215)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>jumping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to OD.
<ets>gumpen</ets>, dial. G. <ets>gumpen</ets>,
<ets>jumpen</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To spring free from the ground by the muscular
action of the feet and legs; to project one's self through the air; to
spring; to bound; to leap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not the worst of the three but <qex>jumps</qex> twelve foot and a
half by the square.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move as if by jumping; to bounce; to jolt.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>jumping</xex> chariots.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Nahum iii.
2.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A flock of geese <qex>jump</qex> down together.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To coincide; to agree; to accord; to tally; --
followed by <ptcl>with</ptcl>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧It <xex>jumps</xex> with my
humor.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To jump at</b></col>, <cd>to spring to; hence, fig., to
accept suddenly or eagerly; <as>as, a fish <ex>jumps at</ex> a bait; to
<ex>jump at</ex> a chance</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Jump
<hw>Jump</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass
over by means of a spring or leap; to overleap; <as>as, to <ex>jump</ex>
a stream</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to jump; <as>as, he <ex>jumped</ex> his
horse across the ditch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To expose to danger; to risk; to hazard.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>jump</qex> a body with a dangerous physic.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Smithwork)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To join by a
butt weld.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To thicken or enlarge by endwise
blows; to upset.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Quarrying)</fld> <def>To bore with a
jumper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To jump a claim</b></col>, <cd>to enter upon and take
possession of land to which another has acquired a claim by prior entry
and occupation.</cd> <mark>[Western U. S. & Australia]</mark> <see>See
<er>Claim</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</see> -- <col><b>To jump one's
bail</b></col>, <cd>to abscond while at liberty under bail bonds.</cd>
<mark>[Slang, U. S.]</mark> -- <col><b>To jump the gun</b></col>, <cd>to
begin to run (in a footrace) before the starting gun has fired; hence,
<mark>(fig.)</mark> to begin any activity before the designated starting
time.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Jump
<hw>Jump</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of jumping; a
leap; a spring; a bound.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To advance by
<xex>jumps</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An effort; an attempt; a venture.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our fortune lies⟦br⟧
Upon this<qex>jump</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The space traversed by a leap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A dislocation in a stratum; a
fault.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An abrupt interruption of level
in a piece of brickwork or masonry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A jump-start; <as>as, to get a <ex>jump</ex> from a
passing motorist</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>From the jump</b></col>, <cd>from the start or
beginning.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>Jump joint</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A butt joint</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A flush joint, as
of plank in carvel-built vessels.</cd> -- <col><b>Jump seat</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A movable carriage seat</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A
carriage constructed with a seat which may be shifted so as to make room
for second or extra seat. Also used adjectively; <as>as, a
<ex>jump-seat</ex> wagon</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jump</ent>⟦br⟧

